msgid "One entry in the vocabulary defines exactly one \"word\". In contrast to the common use of the word \"word\", in simon \"word\" means one unique combination of the following: <itemizedlist> <listitem><para>Wordname</para><para>(The written word itself)</para></listitem> <listitem><para>Terminal</para><para>(Grammatical category; For example: \"Noun\", \"Verb\", etc.)</para></listitem> <listitem><para>Pronunciation</para><para>(How the word is pronounced; simon accepts any kind of phonetic as long as it does not use special characters or numbers)</para></listitem> </itemizedlist> That means that plurals or even different cases are different \"words\" to simon. This is an important design decicion to allow more control when using a sophisticated grammar."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: index.docbook:459
#, no-c-format
msgid "In general, it is advisable to keep your vocabulary as sleek as possible. The more words, the higher the chance that simon might misunderstand you."
